# Evidence-Based Design for LearnLab: Maximising Learning and Engagement in Self-Paced Lessons

## TL;DR
- The strongest learning gains for LearnLab will come from doubling down on what the platform already does well (embedded retrieval checkpoints, worked-example-plus-reveal, interactivity where the idea lands) while adding three under-exploited mechanics with large evidence bases: pretesting/prediction-before-reveal, self-explanation prompts, and cross-lesson spaced retrieval. Retrieval practice (Rowland 2014, g = 0.50), self-explanation (Bisra et al. 2018, g = 0.55), pretesting (Pan & Sana 2021, d ≈ 0.30 over even retrieval practice), and worked-example fading with self-explanation (medium-to-large far-transfer effects) are among the best-supported, cheapest-to-implement techniques available.
- The story/journey approach is supported for *transfer* and *motivation* (narrative instruction beats expository text on transfer at d ≈ 0.42–0.49, especially for lower-prior-knowledge learners) BUT carries a specific, well-replicated failure mode: the seductive-details effect, where interesting-but-irrelevant story elements reduce retention and transfer. The single most important guardrail for a story-based platform is to keep narrative load-bearing (every story beat must carry the concept) and strip decorative detail.
- Gamification (LearnLab's points/streaks/celebrations) reliably raises engagement but can produce shallow "badge tourism" and can undermine intrinsic motivation via the overjustification effect (Deci, Koestner & Ryan 1999: performance-contingent rewards undermine free-choice intrinsic motivation at d = −0.28). Tie every reward to genuine mastery, not activity; calibrate narrative "dosage" down for adults (andragogy); and build the platform capabilities ranked at the end of this report, led by cross-module spaced retrieval, prediction widgets, misconception-targeted feedback, and worked-example fading.

## Key Findings

**Learning science.** The techniques with the highest utility ratings in Dunlosky et al. (2013) are practice testing and distributed practice. Retrieval practice yields a medium-to-large, robust effect: Rowland's (2014, *Psychological Bulletin* 140(6):1432–63) meta-analysis found g = 0.50 [0.42, 0.58] from 159 effect sizes, and feedback "almost doubled the testing benefit" (g = 0.73 with feedback vs g = 0.39 without). Crucially, recall tests outperformed recognition (cued recall g = 0.72, free recall g = 0.82, versus MCQ g = 0.36). This directly validates LearnLab's "checkpoint after every checkable beat" formula — and argues for making checkpoints genuine *recall* attempts with elaborated feedback, not recognition tasks.

**Story/narrative.** Narrative instruction produces medium transfer benefits over expository text (Tobler et al., undergraduate natural science: non-STEM d = 0.42, STEM d = 0.49), and works best for low-prior-knowledge learners, while high-prior-knowledge learners do best with narrative-as-preface-then-exposition. Germane cognitive load and self-efficacy were the mediating mechanisms. The countervailing risk is the seductive-details effect (Harp & Mayer; Rey 2012 meta-analysis: negative effects on retention [small-to-medium] and transfer [medium]).

**Engagement/motivation.** Points/badges/leaderboards reliably raise engagement but the research is mixed on learning; Hanus & Fox (2015) found multiple game elements *reduced* motivation and satisfaction. The overjustification effect (Deci, Koestner & Ryan 1999, *Psychological Bulletin* 125(6):627–668, meta-analysis of 128 studies) found engagement-, completion-, and performance-contingent rewards significantly undermined free-choice intrinsic motivation (d = −0.40, −0.36, and −0.28 respectively). Growth-mindset effects are contested and small on average (Sisk et al. 2018: intervention d = 0.08, 95% CI [0.02, 0.14]; mindset accounted for ~1% of variance in achievement; d = 0.19 for at-risk students).

**Widgets/assessment.** PhET's research shows sims work best with *implicit scaffolding* and *guided inquiry with minimal directions* — the sim's design channels productive exploration without explicit step-by-step instructions. Three-option MCQs are as valid as four/five-option (Rodriguez 2005 meta-analysis of 80 years of research; most items have only ~2 functioning distractors). Distractors should be built from real misconceptions. Elaborated feedback beats correctness-only (van der Kleij: EF 0.49 vs KCR 0.32 vs KR 0.05).

**Platform.** Intelligent tutoring systems produce large gains (VanLehn 2011: ITS d = 0.76 vs no tutoring, nearly matching human tutoring at d = 0.79; ASSISTments RCTs 0.18–0.29 SD; Carnegie Learning MATHia 0.21–0.38 SD). Worked-example fading (backward fading + self-explanation) produces medium-to-large near- and far-transfer gains with no extra time on task.

## Details

### 1. Learning science fundamentals and their LearnLab implications

**Retrieval practice / the testing effect.** This is the best-evidenced single technique. Rowland (2014) found g = 0.50 across 159 effect sizes; Adesope et al. (2017, 118 studies) found g ≈ 0.70. Critically for LearnLab: (a) the effect is substantially larger *with feedback* (Rowland: 0.73 vs 0.39); (b) recall/generation formats beat recognition (Rowland: free recall g = 0.82, cued recall g = 0.72, MCQ g = 0.36), and a *mixture* of formats yields the strongest effect (Adesope et al.); (c) more effortful, complex retrieval produces bigger benefits; (d) even one retrieval event beats none; (e) secondary-school students benefited more than younger or older populations (Adesope). One methodological caveat: a 2023 *Frontiers in Psychology* re-examination argues some of the reported advantage over concept-mapping is a memorisation-time artifact — so the honest position is "large and robust, but not infinite."
- *LearnLab implication:* Keep the one-checkpoint-per-beat formula. Ensure each checkpoint requires *recall/generation* (numeric, text, or a "predict/derive" step) at least as often as recognition (mcq). Every checkpoint must carry elaborated feedback (the platform already mandates explanations — good). Rotate formats within a lesson.

**Spacing, distributed practice and interleaving.** Distributed practice is a top-2 technique in Dunlosky et al. Spacing beats massing for retention (large verbal-memory literature). Interleaving beats blocking for inductive category learning and discrimination (Brunmair & Richter 2019 meta-analysis: overall math effect ≈ 0.34 SD; perceptual category learning g = 0.31–0.67), but the effect is *highly heterogeneous and material-dependent* — for some materials (e.g., expository text) interleaving shows no benefit or even slight harm, and a large classroom math RCT (Rohrer et al.) found only small, non-significant long-term cumulative gains. Interleaving works best when to-be-learned categories are confusable with one another.
- *LearnLab implication:* Interleaving is worth building at the *practice/assessment* level (mixing problem types within a module quiz, and cumulative review that pulls from earlier modules), not by fragmenting the teaching within a single lesson (which would fight the "journey" structure and increase extraneous load). Spacing is best delivered by cross-module spaced retrieval scheduling (see platform recommendations).

**Worked-example effect and expertise reversal.** For novices, studying worked examples beats unguided problem-solving (Sweller & Cooper 1985; Cooper & Sweller 1987). But this reverses as expertise grows — the *expertise reversal effect* (Kalyuga, Ayres, Chandler & Sweller 2003; Kalyuga et al. 2001): worked examples become redundant and even harmful for knowledgeable learners, who learn more by solving. The resolution is *fading* (see §5 and platform recs).
- *LearnLab implication:* LearnLab's "one full derivation + one held-back worked example behind a reveal" is well-aligned for novice-facing content. For higher levels (A-level, adult), shift the ratio toward problem-solving and completion problems. Encode a rule: match worked-example density to the audience's assumed prior knowledge.

**Cognitive load theory.** Distinguish intrinsic (element interactivity of the material), extraneous (poor design), and germane (schema-building) load. Key design effects: split-attention (integrate text and diagrams spatially), redundancy (do NOT duplicate the same information across simultaneous channels — e.g., narration that is also identical on-screen text harms learning when fast-paced), modality (spread information across visual + auditory channels when appropriate), and coherence (exclude extraneous material).
- *LearnLab implication:* Since LearnLab is text + widgets (not narrated video), the redundancy/modality effects apply mainly to figure/caption/label design: put labels *on* diagrams, not in separate legends; never repeat the full explanatory sentence inside a figure that already appears in body text. The coherence principle is the theoretical backbone of the anti-seductive-detail rule.

**Desirable difficulties (Bjork).** Conditions that slow apparent learning (spacing, interleaving, retrieval, generation, varied practice) often improve long-term retention and transfer — "performance during training" is a poor guide to "learning." Soderstrom & Bjork (2015) formalise the learning-vs-performance distinction.
- *LearnLab implication:* Do not optimise checkpoints for a smooth in-lesson success rate. Some productive struggle is desirable. But calibrate — see flow/difficulty below.

**Generation and pretesting effects.** The generation effect: producing an answer beats reading it. The pretesting/prequestion effect (Pan & Carpenter 2023 review; Pan & Sana 2021) is striking: attempting questions *before* instruction — even failing them — improves later retention if correct answers follow, and in a head-to-head, pretesting beat post-testing (retrieval practice) by d = 0.30. Pretesting before video also reduces mind-wandering (Pan, Schmitt, Bjork & Sana 2020). Learners generally under-appreciate this, so they need to be nudged into it.
- *LearnLab implication:* This is a major under-used lever. Open lessons (or sections) with a genuine prequestion or "predict what happens" before the teaching — a perfect fit for the journey "hook" and for a prediction-before-reveal widget. This converts the hook from mere motivation into a measured-learning intervention.

**Self-explanation and elaborative interrogation.** Prompting learners to explain *why* a step works or *how* a new fact connects to prior knowledge produces a robust, sizeable benefit (Bisra, Liu, Nesbit, Salimi & Winne 2018, *Educational Psychology Review* 30:703–725: overall weighted mean g = 0.55 across 69 effect sizes from 64 reports and 5,917 learners; Fiorella & Mayer report d = 0.61). It works across subjects, education levels, and declarative + procedural knowledge. It is *less* effective when learners are asked to explain their own knowledge state (metacognitive) rather than the material.
- *LearnLab implication:* Add self-explanation prompts to reveals and worked examples ("Before you open the next step, explain why we can divide both sides here"). Build a self-explanation prompt type. This is one of the highest-ROI additions available.

**Feedback timing and quality.** Elaborated feedback (explaining why) beats knowledge-of-correct-response beats correctness-only (van der Kleij meta-analysis: EF 0.49, KCR 0.32, KR 0.05; EF especially helps higher-order learning and is strongest in mathematics). Timing (immediate vs delayed) matters less than consistency — recent meta-analyses find both effective, with immediate feedback better for lower-achievers and rapid error correction, delayed feedback sometimes better for higher-order transfer in advanced learners. A confound: delayed feedback is often measured closer to the test (recency), inflating its apparent value.
- *LearnLab implication:* LearnLab's immediate animated feedback is appropriate for self-paced novices. Keep it, but ensure every explanation is genuinely *elaborated* (addresses the misconception behind the wrong answer), not just "Correct! Well done."

**Multimedia/segmenting/dual coding.** Mayer's principles: segmenting (user-paced chunks) improves learning — LearnLab's 150–250-word beats implement this directly. Dual coding (words + relevant visuals) beats words alone (multimedia principle), but only when the visual is relevant (coherence). Signalling (cueing key structure) helps.
- *LearnLab implication:* Every teachable beat should ideally have one relevant visual or interactive, never decorative imagery. Keep chunking. Use callouts as signalling devices for key ideas.

**Learning styles.** For completeness: the "matching instruction to learning styles" hypothesis is not supported by evidence and should never be a design principle. LearnLab should not build "visual vs auditory learner" pathways.

### 2. Story/narrative-based learning: benefits and failure modes

Narrative genuinely helps. Tobler et al. (undergraduate biology/natural science) found narrative instruction beat expository text on *transfer* (non-STEM d = 0.42; STEM d = 0.49), mediated by increased germane cognitive load and self-efficacy. Low-prior-knowledge students benefited most from content embedded in narrative; high-prior-knowledge students benefited most from narrative-as-preface followed by expository content. Storytelling in informal STEM (Haden et al. review; tinkering+storytelling studies) improved retention and transfer in children. Anchored instruction (CTGV / Jasper series) uses a story that leads to a problem the learner must solve, with embedded (and deliberately extraneous) data — training realistic problem-framing and transfer.

Curiosity is the engine. Loewenstein's (1994) information-gap theory: curiosity arises from an awareness of a gap between what one knows and wants to know; a "priming dose" of information sharply increases curiosity, and curiosity rises as one approaches closing the gap. Crucially, curiosity increases the *more* you already know about a topic (someone who knows 8/10 facts is more curious about the missing 2 than someone who knows 2/10). This is the theoretical basis for the "hook with a problem your current toolkit can't solve" opening.

The failure mode: seductive details. Adding interesting-but-irrelevant material (vivid anecdotes, tangential stories, decorative video) reliably *reduces* retention and transfer (Harp & Mayer 1997/1998; Rey 2012 meta-analysis: small-to-medium negative on retention, medium negative on transfer). The mechanisms are distraction, disruption of coherence, and diversion (activating irrelevant prior knowledge). The harm is worst for learners with low working-memory/attention control, and even when they don't disrupt reading they still divert (Bender 2021). Some field studies (a flipped genetics classroom) found no harm and possible affective benefit for high-prior-knowledge students — so the effect is real but context-dependent.
- *The central tension for LearnLab:* what makes content *feel* engaging (a fun tangent, a colourful character, a dramatic aside) is exactly what can *harm* measured learning. The resolution is a hard rule: **narrative must be load-bearing.** Every story element must carry the concept forward (be the vehicle for the idea, the source of the problem, or the thread that structures the sequence). If a detail could be deleted without weakening the concept, delete it.

### 3. Engagement and motivation mechanics

**Self-determination theory (SDT).** Autonomy, competence, and relatedness are the core drivers of durable, intrinsic motivation. Ed-tech that supports genuine choice (autonomy), well-calibrated challenge with clear progress (competence), and connection (relatedness) sustains engagement better than pure reward loops.
- *LearnLab implication:* Competence is served by LearnLab's mastery checkpoints and immediate feedback; autonomy by self-pacing and (a possible addition) optional depth/branches; relatedness is currently thin (single-player) — a candidate area, though peer features carry moderation cost.

**Points, badges, streaks.** They reliably raise engagement, completion, and return visits (Hamari, Koivisto & Sarsa 2014). But: (a) "BPL gamification" (bolting Badges/Points/Leaderboards onto an unchanged experience) underperforms; (b) Hanus & Fox (2015) found multiple game elements *reduced* motivation and satisfaction over a semester; (c) the overjustification effect (Deci, Koestner & Ryan 1999, 128 studies) shows extrinsic rewards for already-intrinsically-interesting tasks erode intrinsic motivation, with free-choice intrinsic motivation undermined at d = −0.40 (engagement-contingent), −0.36 (completion-contingent), and −0.28 (performance-contingent). Duolingo's own research shows streak mechanics (e.g., Streak Wager) measurably lift retention (Day-7 retention +14%), and that *lessons completed* predicted learning more than time spent — i.e., the mechanics work when they drive genuine practice volume.
- *LearnLab implication:* Keep celebrations and streaks, but tie every reward to *mastery* milestones ("mastered vectors"), not trivial activity (logging in, opening a lesson). Prefer competence-signalling rewards (badges for demonstrated skill) over inflationary points. Avoid competitive leaderboards as a default (they demotivate beginners and those behind).

**Flow and difficulty calibration.** Flow requires challenge matched to skill. Combined with desirable-difficulty theory, the target is a success rate high enough to sustain competence but low enough to require genuine retrieval/generation. Immediate feedback loops (LearnLab has these) are a flow prerequisite.
- *LearnLab implication:* Aim checkpoints at a moderate-but-not-trivial difficulty; build adaptive difficulty later (platform rec).

**Mastery vs performance framing; growth mindset.** Mastery-based framing (improvement, not ranking) aligns with SDT. Growth-mindset messaging is popular but its average effect is small and contested: Sisk et al. (2018, *Psychological Science*) two meta-analyses found the correlation with achievement weak (~1% variance, k=273, N=365,915) and intervention effect d = 0.08 [0.02, 0.14], although the effect was larger (d = 0.19) for academically at-risk students, and defenders (Yeager, Dweck) argue heterogeneity hides real effects for specific subgroups (low-SES, at-risk) in well-implemented interventions.
- *LearnLab implication:* Use mastery framing and effort-and-strategy praise in encouraging voice (already in house style), but do NOT over-invest in explicit growth-mindset "lectures" — the evidence doesn't justify prominence. Encouraging feedback should attribute success to *strategy and effort on this task*, not innate ability, and keep it brief.

**Platform comparisons.** Duolingo's published work (in *Foreign Language Annals*, announced January 2022) showed learners who completed five units in the Spanish or French courses "performed as well on reading and listening tests as students who had completed four semesters of university language instruction," and did so "in less than half the time"; Duolingo treats notifications/streaks as core, rigorously A/B-tested features (500+ simultaneous tests). Brilliant.org's stated philosophy is the closest analogue to LearnLab's widget-heavy approach and is examined in §5.

### 4. Age-span considerations ("for all ages")

Knowles's andragogy contrasts adult learners (self-directed, experience-rich, problem-oriented, internally motivated, need-to-know-why, immediate-application) with pedagogy's more teacher-directed model. Knowles himself later reframed pedagogy–andragogy as a *continuum* from teacher-directed to self-directed, appropriate to the situation rather than strictly age-bound. Adults are more resistant to drills, rote, and content they can't see the point of; they want relevance and autonomy.

Developmental differences: younger teens (GCSE ~14–16) have shorter sustained attention, weaker self-regulation, and greater tolerance for (and benefit from) narrative framing and characters; A-level (~16–18) are transitional; adults prefer directness, respect for their time, and problem/goal-oriented framing, and can find heavy story scaffolding patronising.

Retrieval-practice benefits were actually largest for secondary students (Adesope et al.), so the checkpoint formula scales across the span. Narrative benefits low-prior-knowledge learners most regardless of age — so "adult" doesn't mean "no narrative," it means "narrative calibrated to prior knowledge and delivered with less whimsy."
- *LearnLab implication — narrative dosage dial:* Encode an explicit audience parameter that scales (a) narrative density and playfulness, (b) worked-example vs problem-solving ratio, (c) directness of tone, and (d) assumed prior knowledge. GCSE: richer story, more worked examples, more scaffolding, characters okay. A-level: story as problem-frame and throughline, balanced worked/solve, concise. Adult/foundation-for-professionals: minimal whimsy, narrative used only as a real-world problem anchor and structural throughline, lead with why-it-matters and application, more independent problem-solving. The *journey structure itself* (hook → throughline → payoff) is valuable at all ages; it is the *whimsy and character dosage* that must fall with age.

### 5. Interactive widget and assessment design

**Simulations/manipulables (PhET).** PhET's research (Wieman, Perkins, Adams, Podolefsky, Moore) shows sims are most effective when: (a) embedded in *guided inquiry with minimal explicit directions*; (b) using *implicit scaffolding* — the sim's scope, layout, controls, and feedback channel productive exploration "without feeling guided"; (c) starting with brief open exploration before targeted tasks; (d) allowing quantitative pattern exploration (more effective for moving learners to higher understanding than purely qualitative sims). A literature review (Banda & Nzabanimana 2021, 31 studies) reported learning gains 37% greater than control. The lesson: a good sim is not a toy — it constrains the space so that "playing" produces the intended conceptual insight.
- *LearnLab implication:* LearnLab's sims (function-grapher, vector-field, circuit-sim, logic-gate-sim, geometry-canvas) should each ship with (a) a short open-exploration prompt, (b) implicit scaffolding baked into defaults/ranges/labels so the first thing a learner does is pedagogically productive, and (c) a specific prediction or pattern-finding task. Rule: never drop a sim in without a "try to make X happen / predict what happens if…" prompt.

**Prediction before reveal.** The single highest-value sim/widget pattern combining pretesting + generation + curiosity: ask the learner to predict an outcome, commit to it, then run/reveal. Directly supported by pretesting (§1) and the design philosophy of both PhET and Brilliant.

**Flashcards and spacing.** Flashcards are effective when they drive retrieval and are spaced; their value multiplies with a scheduling algorithm (see platform recs). Card design: one fact per card, cue→response recall, avoid overloaded cards.

**MCQ design.** Well-supported rules: (a) three options is optimal — Rodriguez's 2005 meta-analysis ("Three options are optimal for multiple-choice items: A meta-analysis of 80 years of research," *Educational Measurement: Issues and Practice* 24(2):3–13), which concluded "more 3-option items can be administered than 4- or 5-option items per testing time while improving content coverage, without detrimental effects on psychometric quality"; most items have only ~2 functioning distractors (Tarrant et al.); fewer options = less reading load, more items per test, easier authoring, and benefits non-native English speakers; (b) build distractors from *real, documented misconceptions* (Haladyna) so wrong answers diagnose thinking; (c) avoid "none/all of the above" and double negatives; (d) multiple-true-false reveals student thinking more thoroughly than single-best-answer (Bayesian IRT comparison). 
- *LearnLab implication:* Default quiz MCQs to 3 options with misconception-based distractors, each with an explanation that names and corrects the misconception. This is a concrete, mechanical rule an AI author can follow.

**Confidence-based marking and two-tier diagnostics.** Two-tier questions (answer + reason) diagnose misconceptions far better than single-tier. Confidence-based marking surfaces the dangerous "confidently wrong" state and encourages metacognitive calibration.

**Open-response vs recognition.** Recall/generation produces bigger testing effects than recognition (Rowland: free recall g = 0.82 vs MCQ g = 0.36). LearnLab's numeric and text types enable this; use them more than mcq for core procedural skills.

**Hints, scaffolding, and ITS findings.** ITS meta-analyses: well-designed ITS d = 0.76 SD over no tutoring, nearly matching human tutoring at d = 0.79 (VanLehn 2011, *Educational Psychologist* 46(4):197–221). A K-12 ITS meta-analysis found just-in-time hints g = 0.337, worked-out examples g = 0.324, on-demand hints g = 0.316 — all modestly effective; elaborated feedback/explanations were universal. Hint-design cautions: purely optional hints can speed completion without improving learning (Anderson et al. 1995); students often *avoid* help or abuse "bottom-out" hints; scaffolded/subgoal hints ("Waypoints") that require the learner to do 2–3 steps preserve productive effort. Mastery learning (move on only when a skill threshold is reached; Bayesian knowledge tracing) underpins Carnegie Learning and ALEKS.

**Worked-example fading (backward fading + self-explanation).** This is a stand-out, precisely-specified technique (Renkl & Atkinson 2003; Atkinson, Renkl & Merrill 2003; Salden et al. 2010). The procedure, in Renkl & Atkinson's (2003) own words: "First, a complete example is presented (model). Second, an example is given in which one single solution step is omitted (coached problem solving). Then, the number of blanks is increased step by step until just the problem formulation is left." **Backward fading** (remove the *last* step first, then the last two, etc.) beats forward fading and example-problem pairs: it produced the significant far-transfer benefit and required *less* learning time (Renkl & Atkinson 2003; effects η² ≈ .08–.23). Fading *alone* reliably improves near transfer but not far transfer; *adding self-explanation prompts* at each worked step (asking the learner to name the underlying principle) extends the benefit to *far* transfer with medium-to-large effects and no extra time on task (Atkinson, Renkl & Merrill 2003, *Journal of Educational Psychology* 95(4):774–783). Best of all is *adaptive* fading — fade at the pace of each learner's demonstrated understanding (Salden et al. 2010, *Instructional Science* 38(3):289–307: adaptive fading > fixed fading > problem-solving on delayed transfer, implemented in the Geometry Cognitive Tutor).

**Brilliant.org as comparison.** Brilliant's public philosophy ("Learn by doing"; "active problem solving... shown to be far more effective than passive learning like videos or lectures") is the closest large-scale analogue to LearnLab's widget-heavy lessons. Their stated method: single-concept lessons, visual/interactive-first, "we don't teach how to do something before asking questions... we pretest on the material, letting the learner try to find a solution before learning the procedure" (a productive-failure/pretesting stance), instant custom feedback per answer, and scaffolding that "falls away" in practice sets ("no more visual aids or hints") and in their AI tutor ("Koji offers more help when you're learning a new topic, and steps back when it's time to test your knowledge... make himself unnecessary"). Caveat: these are first-party marketing claims; Brilliant publishes no independent peer-reviewed efficacy study of its own platform. Still, its convergence with the fading and pretesting literatures is instructive: LearnLab is philosophically on the right track and should push *further* toward prediction-before-instruction and fading scaffolds.

